### Anaphora
**Definition:** Repeating the same word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses or sentences.
**Example:** "We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds, we shall fight in the fields..." (Churchill)
**Effect:** Builds momentum and power; drills a message into the reader/listener; creates a rallying, forceful effect.

---

### Epistrophe
**Definition:** Repeating the same word or phrase at the END of successive clauses.
**Example:** "...government of the people, by the people, for the people." (Lincoln)
**Effect:** Creates emphasis and closure; draws attention to the repeated concept; establishes a circular, resonant rhythm.

---

### Parallelism
**Definition:** Using the same grammatical structure in successive phrases or clauses.
**Example:** "She came, she saw, she conquered."
**Effect:** Creates balance, rhythm, and elegance; makes writing feel structured and authoritative.

---

### Symbolism
**Definition:** Using an object, place, character, or event to represent an abstract idea.
**Example:** A wilting flower symbolising the end of a relationship; a locked door symbolising an inability to escape the past.
**Effect:** Adds layers of meaning; allows writers to convey complex ideas without stating them directly; rewards thoughtful readers.

---

### Euphemism
**Definition:** A mild or indirect word used in place of something blunt, harsh, or taboo.
**Example:** "He passed away" instead of "he died"; "collateral damage" instead of "civilian casualties."
**Effect:** Softens harsh realities; allows speakers to address sensitive topics with tact; can obscure truth or manipulate perception.

---

### Oxymoron
**Definition:** Combining two contradictory terms in a single phrase.
**Example:** "deafening silence," "bittersweet," "living death," "open secret"
**Effect:** Captures paradox; creates intrigue; forces readers to hold opposing ideas simultaneously.

---

### Synecdoche
**Definition:** A part representing the whole, or vice versa.
**Example:** "All hands on deck" (hands = people); "the Crown decided" (Crown = monarchy)
**Effect:** Creates vivid, economical imagery; can dehumanise or isolate one aspect of a person or institution.

