eration of '...' creates a sense of...\" |\n| Repetition | \"The repetition of '...' emphasises...\" |\n| Rhetorical question | \"The rhetorical question '...' challenges the reader to...\" |\n| Short sentence | \"The short, declarative sentence '...' creates a sudden sense of...\" |\n| Listing / tricolon | \"The list of '...' accumulates detail to overwhelm the reader with...\" |\n| Emotive language | \"The emotive language '...' provokes a sense of...\" |\n| Juxtaposition | \"The juxtaposition of '...' and '...' highlights the contrast between...\" |\n| Pathetic fallacy | \"The pathetic fallacy of '...' mirrors the character's inner state of...\" |\n| Hyperbole | \"The hyperbole '...' exaggerates to emphasise the extent of...\" |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Summary Writing — Step-by-Step Checklist\n\n- [ ] Read the source text fully at least once\n- [ ] Re-read and annotate / underline only the key relevant points\n- [ ] Check exactly what the question is asking you to summarise\n- [ ] Select 6–10 distinct, non-overlapping points directly relevant to the question\n- [ ] Rephrase each point in your own words (synonyms + restructured sentences)\n- [ ] Write an opening sentence that addresses the question directly\n- [ ] Use linking phrases to connect points smoothly into flowing prose\n- [ ] Stay within the target word count (typically 100–200 words)\n- [ ] Do NOT include your own opinions or add extra information\n- [ ] Check: have you copied anything word-for-word? If yes, rephrase it\n\n---\n\n## 5. Directed Writing Forms — Format Conventions\n\n| Form | Key Layout Features | Opening | Closing |\n|------|-------------------|---------|---------|\n| Formal letter | Sender address (top right), date, recipient address (left) | Dear Sir/Madam | Yours faithfully |\n| Informal letter | Less rigid layout, friendly tone, contractions fine | Dear [First Name] | Yours sincerely / Love / Best wishes |\n| Speech | Greeting, rhetorical devices, direct address to audience | \"Good morning,