  "new_text": "# 📖 Chapter 4: Directed Writing\n\n> [[03. Summary Writing|← Ch 3]] | [[05. Narrative Writing|Ch 5 →]]\n\n---\n\n## 4.1 What Is Directed Writing?\n\nDirected writing is a task where you must:\n1. **Read** a source text carefully\n2. **Write a response** in a specified form (e.g., a letter, speech, article, report)\n3. **Draw on and adapt material from the source text** — selecting, rephrasing, and expanding on it\n4. **Write for a specific, stated audience and purpose**\n5. **Use the appropriate register, layout, and language** for the given form\n\nThe task will always tell you:\n- **What form** to write in (letter, report, speech, article, interview, etc.)\n- **Who the audience is** (a headteacher, the general public, a friend, a newspaper reader, etc.)\n- **What the purpose is** (to persuade, inform, advise, entertain, etc.)\n\n> [!note] Directed writing tests TWO things simultaneously: your ability to extract and adapt information from the source text, AND your ability to write convincingly in the specified form. You must do BOTH to earn high marks.\n\n---\n\n## 4.2 Forms and Their Layout Conventions\n\n### Master Layout Reference Table\n\n| Form | Key Layout Features | Opening | Closing |\n|------|-------------------|---------|---------|\n| **Formal letter** | Sender address (top right), date below, recipient name/address (left), formal salutation, paragraphs | Dear Sir/Madam | Yours faithfully |\n| **Informal letter** | Optional address, friendly tone, contractions acceptable, paragraphs | Dear [First Name] | Yours sincerely / With love / Best wishes |\n| **Speech** | Address audience directly, rhetorical devices, direct address (\"you\"), sign off | \"Good morning, ladies and gentlemen / Fellow students\" | \"Thank you for listening / for your time\" |\n| **Newspaper article** | Bold or CAPS headline, byline (By [Name]), opening paragraph covering 5 Ws, subheadings, quotes from sources, third person | Headline in bold | No formal closing — article ends naturally |\n| **Magazine article** | Engaging headline, subheadings, may use pull quotes, tone matches target readership | Hook sentence / attention-grabbing opening | Strong final thought or call to action |\n| **Report** | Clear title, formal headings (Introduction / Findings / Recommendations / Conclusion), impersonal tone, may use numbered sections | \"Introduction\" section | \"Recommendations\" or \"Conclusion\" section |\n| **Interview** | Q&A format, interviewer name/role on left, natural but purposeful questions, interviewee's full responses | \"Interviewer: Thank you for joining us today...\" | \"Interviewer: Thank you for your time.\" |\n| **Email** | Subject line, appropriate greeting, sign-off appropriate to relationship | Subject: [Topic] | Regards / Best wishes / [Name] |\n\n---\n\n### Formal Letter Layout — Full Template\n\n```\n                                    [Your Address Line 1]\n                                    [Town, County, Postcode]\n                                    [Date written in full: 14 January 2027]\n\n[Recipient's Title and Name, if known]\n[Organisation / School / Company]\n[Recipient's Address]\n\nDear Sir/Madam,  [if name unknown]\nDear Mr/Ms [Surname],  [if name known]\n\n[Opening paragraph: state clearly who you are and why you are writing]\n\n[Body paragraph 1: first main point — developed with evidence and explanation]\n\n[Body paragraph 2: second main point — developed with evidence and explanation]\n\n[Body paragraph 3: third main point or counter-argument / emotional appeal]\n\n[Closing paragraph: summarise your position; make a specific request or call to action]\n\nYours faithfully,  [if you opened with 'Dear Sir/Madam']\nYours sincerely,  [if you opened with the person's name]\n\n[Your Full Name]\n```\n\n> 💡 **Exam tip:** The Yours faithfully / Yours sincerely distinction is a classic exam trap. Remember: **faithfully if you don't know the name** (both begin with a repeated-first-letter); **sincerely if you do know the name**.\n\n---\n\n### Speech Layout — Full Template\n\n```\n[Appropriate greeting for the audience]\nGood morning, ladies and gentlemen,\nFellow students,\nMembers of the committee,\n\n[Hook — rhetorical question, shocking statistic, bold statement, or anecdote]\n\n[Body — develop your main arguments using AFOREST persuasive techniques;\n         use direct address (\"you\"), inclusive language (\"we\"), and rhetorical questions\n         to maintain engagement]\n\n[Counter-argument and rebuttal — if applicable]\n\n[Conclusion — summarise your key message; end with a memorable line or call to action]\n\nThank you for listening.\nThank you for your time and attention.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Newspaper Article Layout — Full Template\n\n```\n[HEADLINE IN BOLD CAPITALS — Short, punchy, engaging]\n\nBy [Your Name], [Publication Name], [Date]\n\n[Opening paragraph: answers Who, What, Where, When, Why — the most important information first]\n\n[Paragraph 2: Develop the story with context and background detail]\n\n[Subheading in bold]\n[Paragraph 3: Further details, statistics, expert quotes]\n\n[Subheading in bold]\n[Paragraph 4: Eyewitness/participant quotes; human interest angle]\n\n[Final paragraph: Future implications, expert opinion, or closing statement]\n```\n\n---\n\n### Report Layout — Full Template\n\n```\nREPORT ON: [Subject of the report]\nPrepared by: [Your name/role]\nDate: [Date]\n\n1. Introduction\n   [State the purpose of the report and the issue being investigated]\n\n2. Findings\n   [Present the main information gathered, organised by sub-point]\n   2.1 [First finding]\n   2.2 [Second finding]\n   2.3 [Third finding]\n\n3. Conclusion\n   [Brief summary of the key findings]\n\n4. Recommendations\n   [Numbered, specific, actionable suggestions based on the findings]\n   1. ...\n   2. ...\n   3. ...\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4.3 Identifying Audience and Purpose\n\nBefore writing a single word of your response, identify these three elements from the task: