  "new_text": "# 📖 Chapter 5: Narrative Writing\n\n> [[04. Directed Writing|← Ch 4]] | [[06. Descriptive Writing|Ch 6 →]]\n\n---\n\n## 5.1 Story Structure — Freytag's Pyramid\n\nThe classic five-stage narrative arc, known as Freytag's Pyramid, provides a reliable structure for any story:\n\n```\n                         ▲\n                        /|\\\n                       / | \\\n          Rising       /  |  \\   Falling\n          Action      /   |   \\  Action\n                     /    |    \\\n     Exposition ───/      |     \\─── Resolution\n                       CLIMAX\n```\n\n| Stage | Description | What to Include |\n|-------|-------------|----------------|\n| **Exposition** | Introduces the characters, setting, and initial situation | Establish the \"normal world\" — who, where, and when; hint at the coming conflict |\n| **Rising Action** | Tension and conflict build; events complicate the situation | Obstacles, complications, character under pressure; reader's anxiety increases |\n| **Climax** | The turning point — the moment of greatest tension or change | The most dramatic or significant single event in the story |\n| **Falling Action** | Consequences of the climax unfold | The aftermath; things begin to settle or unravel |\n| **Resolution** | The situation is resolved — happily, tragically, or ambiguously | Final state of characters and world; any unanswered questions are closed or deliberately left open |\n\n### Exam Reality — Streamlined Structure\n\nIn a timed exam (30–40 minutes for one writing question), you cannot write all five full stages. Use this practical approach instead:\n\n```\nOPENING    →  Hook the reader immediately (in medias res, mystery, dialogue)\nBODY       →  Build tension toward one central dramatic moment\nCLIMAX     →  The turning point — your most powerful writing\nENDING     →  A single strong closing beat (twist, reflection, circular reference)\n```\n\n> 💡 **Exam tip:** Quality and control matter far more than length. An examiner would rather read 400 words of excellent, controlled narrative than 800 words of rushed, undeveloped writing. Plan for 5 minutes, write for 30 minutes, check for 5 minutes.\n\n---\n\n## 5.2 Narrative Perspectives and Their Effects\n\nChoose ONE perspective and maintain it throughout your story. Switching is a serious error.\n\n| Perspective | Description | Effect | Best Used When |\n|------------|-------------|--------|---------------|\n| **1st person (\"I\")** | Narrator is a character within the story | Deep intimacy and immediacy; limits view to one perspective; narrator may be unreliable | You want the reader to feel \"inside\" the character's experience |\n| **2nd person (\"you\")** | Reader is directly addressed as the protagonist | Unusual and immersive; pulls reader into the story; can feel disorientating | You want a distinctive, unconventional effect |\n| **3rd person limited** | Narrator uses \"he/she/they\" but stays close to one character's perspective | Some intimacy; slightly more distance than 1st person; still focused view | You want closeness with one character but slightly more narrative freedom |\n| **3rd person omniscient** | Narrator knows all characters' thoughts and feelings | God-like view; can provide dramatic irony; broader scope | Longer stories where multiple characters' perspectives matter |\n\n### Unreliable Narrators\nA first-person narrator whose account the reader cannot fully trust is a sophisticated technique. Signs of unreliability:\n- The narrator misunderstands events\n- Other characters' actions contradict what the narrator says\n- The narrator's emotional state distorts their account\n\n---\n\n## 5.3 Opening Techniques — Hooking the Reader\n\nThe first paragraph of your story is the most important. It must grab the reader immediately.\n\n| Technique | How It Works | Strong Example |\n|-----------|-------------|---------------|\n| **In medias res** | Begin in the middle of the action — no preamble or slow build-up | *\"The car was already on fire when she pulled him out.\"* |\n| **Dialogue opener** | Begin with a line of speech that raises immediate questions | *\"'Don't look down,' he said. I looked down.\"* |\n| **Setting / atmosphere** | Create a vivid, atmospheric scene that immediately establishes mood | *\"The village had been silent for three days. No birds. No wind. Nothing at all.\"* |\n| **Mystery / hook** | An intriguing statement that poses immediate questions | *\"The last thing I remember before the accident is laughing.\"* |\n| **Character revelation** | Dive straight into revealing something unusual about a character | *\"My grandmother had one rule: she never lied. She had two thousand exceptions.\"* |\n| **Second person address** | Involve the reader directly | *\"You have been here before, though you do not know it yet.\"* |\n| **Shocking statement** | A surprising opening fact or claim | *\"By the time I realised what she had done, it was already too late to stop her.\"* |\n\n> [!note] Avoid opening with \"It was a dark and stormy night,\" \"Once upon a time,\" or waking up from a dream — these are clichéd and signal to examiners that the writer lacks originality.\n\n---\n\n## 5.4 Character Development — Showing, Not Telling\n\nStrong characters are revealed through action, dialogue, and detail — not through physical description or direct statements about personality.\n\n| Method | What It Does | Example |\n|--------|------------|---------|\n| **Action** | Character's choices under pressure reveal their values and personality | He doesn't say he's generous — he quietly pays for a stranger's meal and says nothing |\n| **Dialogue** | What and how a character speaks reveals personality, relationships, and emotional state | Speaks in clipped, defensive sentences when asked about her family |\n| **Thought / internal monologue** | Reveals the gap between what a character shows and what they feel | *She smiled. Nodded. Said of course, it was fine. It was not fine.*