ction as the story progresses.\n\n**Block description (weak):**\n> *\"The house was old. It had cracked walls and broken windows. The garden was overgrown.\"*\n\n**Woven into action (strong):**\n> *\"She pushed open the gate — it resisted, hinges thick with rust. Her shoe sank into the grass, which was so high it reached her knee. She did not look at the windows. She knew what she would see.\"*\n\n---\n\n## 5.6 Dialogue — Rules and Techniques\n\n### Punctuation Rules for Speech:\n\n```\n\"I don't believe you,\" she said, her voice barely a whisper.\n                        ↑ comma before the speech tag; lowercase 'she'\n\n\"You should,\" he replied. \"It happened exactly as I described.\"\n             ↑ full stop ends the tag; new speech starts with capital letter\n\n\"Then why,\" Maria pressed, \"did no one else see it?\"\n            ↑ tag interrupts speech; comma before and after the tag; lowercase continues\n```\n\n### Key Dialogue Rules:\n- Start a **new paragraph** for each new speaker — every time\n- Punctuation goes **inside** the closing quotation marks\n- Use a **comma** before the speech tag if the speech could continue\n- Use a **full stop** if the speech ends a complete thought and no tag follows\n- Vary your speech tags — whispered, muttered, snapped, demanded, insisted — but don't force unusual tags where \"said\" works better\n\n### Functions of Dialogue in Narrative:\n\n| Function | Example Use |\n|----------|------------|\n| **Reveal character** | What people say and how they say it tells us who they are |\n| **Advance plot** | Characters share information that moves the story forward |\n| **Create conflict** | Disagreement, misunderstanding, tension between characters |\n| **Control pace** | Short, snappy dialogue speeds the narrative; longer exchanges slow it |\n| **Provide context** | Exposition delivered through natural conversation feels less forced |\n\n---\n\n## 5.7 \"Show Don't Tell\" — The Most Important Principle\n\n\"Show don't tell\" means demonstrating an emotion, quality, or idea through specific details, actions, and sensory language — rather than simply stating it.\n\n| Telling (Weak) | Showing (Strong) |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| \"She was nervous.\" | \"She wound the strap of her bag over and over her fingers, her eyes darting to the clock above the door.\" |\n| \"He was furious.\" | \"He set the coffee cup down with such deliberate, controlled care that the counter cracked.\" |\n| \"The place felt sad.\" | \"Toys lay scattered in the mud. A single wellington boot sat by the gate, waiting for a foot that would never return.\" |\n| \"It was bitterly cold.\" | \"Her breath came in clouds. She pressed her hands deep into her armpits and tried, unsuccessfully, not to shiver.\" |\n| \"She was brave.\" | \"Her hands were shaking. She walked in anyway.\" |\n\n> 💡 **Exam tip:** Every time you write a sentence that starts with \"she was [emotion]\" or \"he felt [adjective],\" stop and rewrite it as a piece of showing. This single habit will transform the quality of your narrative writing.\n\n---\n\n## 5.8 Pacing — Controlling Speed\n\nPacing is how fast or slow a narrative feels. It is controlled through deliberate language and structural choices.\n\n| Technique | Effect on Pace | When to Use It |\n|-----------|---------------|---------------|\n| **Short, simple sentences** | Speeds up; creates tension, urgency, action | Action scenes; moments of shock; building to a climax |\n| **Long, flowing sentences** | Slows down; suits reflection, description, calm | Calm moments; character thought; setting description |\n| **Dialogue** | Speeds up; dynamic and immediate | Tense exchanges; arguments; plot-advancing conversations |\n| **Rich description** | Slows down; immerses the reader in detail | Key setting moments; before or after the climax |\n| **Time jumps** | Speeds up narrative time; skips over less important events | Transitioning between scenes; moving forward in time |\n| **Slow motion moments** | Expands a single moment with minute, intense detail | The climax; a moment of revelation; an act of violence or crisis |\n\n### Pacing Example — The Same Event at Two Speeds:\n\n**Fast (action, tension):**\n> *She ran. Door. Stairs. Another door. The sound behind her — closer now. She didn't look back.*\n\n**Slow (reflection, calm):**\n> *She sat at the window for a long while, watching the light change on the garden below — the way it shifted from gold to amber to a pale, exhausted grey, as if the day itself were reluctant to end.*\n\n---\n\n## 5.9 Narrative Arc Planning — Quick Brainstorm Method\n\nIn the exam, spend 5 minutes planning before you write. Use this template:\n\n```\n1. HOOK:     What is the first sentence? (Write it before anything else)\n2. WHO:      1–2 main characters — give each a clear want and a flaw\n3. WHERE:    Setting — one vivid sensory detail you will use\n4. TENSION:  What is the central conflict? (internal / external / both)\n5. CLIMAX:   What is the turning point — the single most dramatic moment?\n6. END:      Final line — does it resolve, twist, reflect, or open up?\n```\n\n> 💡 **Exam tip:** The most common reason for weak narrative endings is not planning ahead. Write your ending in your plan BEFORE you begin writing the story. This means you can build towards it deliberately, creating foreshadowing and coherence.\n\n---\n\n## 5.10 Ending Techniques\n\nYour final paragraph is the last impression you leave. Make it count.\n\n| Ending Type | Description | Effect |\n|------------|-------------|--------|\n| **Circular ending** | Ends with an echo of how it began — a repeated image, phrase, or situation | Creates a satisfying sense of completeness; can suggest stasis or irony if nothing has truly changed |\n| **Twist ending** | Reveals new information that reframes everything the reader thought they understood | Surprises and satisfies; makes the reader want to re-read |\n| **Open ending** | The conflict is not fully reso